description:
Despite having the slogan 'designed to be deleted,' boardroom meetings at Match Group say otherwise. Executives have made it their mission to keep us on the apps longer, turning loneliness into profit.

I am creating these videos for entertainment and educational purposes. Please do not contact or harass any individuals featured in the clips. These clips are included to critique broader trends in the tech industry, particularly where innovation is used to justify exploitative or user-unfriendly practices. I do not condone online bullying or harassment in any form. 

If you enjoyed this content, please consider subscribing to the channel!

comments.text:
10 years ago, I first got on dating apps. I'm 6' 6", was 36 at the time, very handsome, very jacked, have an master's degree from a top 10 university and have been making a six figure income since my mid 20s. I killed it on these apps especially POF and Match. I only sent messages to women who had intelligent, very well written profiles and who seemed to be self-sustaining. Looks were 4th or 5th in my criteria. I would conservatively say that 90% of the women I messaged, wrote me back and I was getting 10-15 likes or messages per day from women I hadn't messaged. 10 years later I try it again not knowing Match owned everything. I'm 46 (look 10 years younger) am still very muscular, still handsome, very successful in my career and debt free. I realized that being 10 years older, I'm going to get less matches because of age but I had my female friend show me the guys on Match and POF that I was competing with and she told me that I was certainly top 1% on the site. The first thing I noticed was how many fewer women were on the apps. I'd say it had dropped by 75% from 10 years earlier. I also noticed many filtered or flattering angled photos and very few body shots. My percentage of messages received back dropped to maybe 50% from 90% 10 years earlier and instead of 10-15 new likes/messages a day, I was averaging 3 or 4. I was also very disappointed in the quality. I had to lower my standards to find women I might connect with. I found two women that I thought were a great match. I went out on 5 dates before cancelling and here are how the dates went:

Date 1: The woman spent two hours reading me texts from her ex telling her what a horrible person she was and listening to hear defend herself and bash him. I listened for two hours because it was rather fascinating but obviously there was no second date.

Date 2:  Woman (looking 10 years older than her photos) tells me that I'm her 100th online date. I asked how long she had been doing it expecting her to say 3-5 years. Her answer was 3 months (over a date per day). I excused myself less than 2 minutes into the date and she cursed me out. 

Date 3:  Woman was drinking when I picked her up at her VERY nice home. At the restaurant she had 3 margaritas in less than half an hour. I informed her that I would gladly pay for dinner and a drink but not pay for her to pound all night. She said she liked to drink and would pay half the bill anyway and thought it was actually "alpha" of me to call her out. She had 8 total drinks and our bill was over $200 with tip. When I asked for her share, she said she'd just pay on our second date. I told her I had no interest in that after her power drinking display. She started yelling causing a scene. I booked her an Uber. She proceeded to send me nasty texts that night.

Date 4:  Started out amazing. Had a couple drinks, made out in my car, set up a second date. Next day she calls saying she showed her BFF my profile and the BFF said she had messaged me and I had never responded (so what?). Says she can't cross her BFF and she can't see me anymore. 

Date 5:  Great date. Had dinner. Made out for a couple hours. She tells me it's her best first date ever. Sends me wonderful texts all week and she's excited for our date on Saturday. Saturday, 3 hours before our date, she calls and says her daughter is horribly ill and asks if we can postpone until the following evening. I said no problem. A few hours later I'm with my buddy at a bar to see a band and who do I see dancing and drinking.....the woman who said her daughter was horribly sick. I walk up to her to confront her and she apologizes and asks for a second chance. I said no thanks. 

Never again for me and online dating.

I was out of an emotionally destabilising relationship and I needed to distract myself, so I decided to download Tinder. Completed my profile and boom, I got 19 likes in just something like two or three days. I was super happy about it of course, confident. 
After those days, I suddenly stopped receiving likes. I had the app totally for two weeks and received maybe just one new like after that initial spike. 19 likes in two days and than one in a week and a half. Quite unprobable, huh? This made me realise just how much the visibility of your profile is controlled by an algorithm: you get rewarded as soon as you create your profile, and than suddenly you are thrown in the trash, which makes you more desperate and inclined to buy the subscription. 
Fuck that soulless CEO.

comments.text:
10:55 Regarding scarcity - I discovered they were doing this nearly 10 years ago when more than 98% of my matches were men with whom I had absolutely NOTHING in common. (I'm an analyst in another industry and was equipped to track my match statistics.) It wasn't just looks, but also a lack of common interests, lifestyle, intellect, and general values. The dating apps completely changed, what felt like, overnight. It took time (a few years of jumping on and off again) before I fully understood it wasn't anything I had been doing wrong. (I had a very descriptive profile with lots of current, full body photos - none of which had been filtered or photo shopped; I'm a very physically fit, relatively attractive all-natural female; I have a stable income with zero debt and own a house and car, free and clear; I have no children and very little baggage; I'm also quite down to earth and attempted to initiate contact regularly.) For all the guys who claimed they get no responses from women, I was baffled because few of them replied to me. It seemed as if my "likes" and messages were just going into an abyss. 

Through an in-person social networking event in 2019, I met an attractive guy who revealed he was on the same popular dating app I had been using. I was skeptical because I had never seen his profile despite the countless hours upon weeks, months, and years I had been scouring the app. So I pulled out my phone to look for him, yet I couldn't find him anywhere, even after plugging his exact description into my preferences. Just to prove that he was on the same app, he pulled up his profile on his phone and showed me that his profile was indeed active and public (meaning anyone could see it). The funny thing is he couldn't find me either. Together, we checked and adjusted our filters to make sure there was nothing that prevented us from finding each other, but to no avail. It was as if the app was deliberately trying to keep us apart.

We ended up dating for a few months until I was unexpectedly transferred out of country on a year-long work assignment, but the experience allowed me to see the dating app, despite being one of the most popular and "successful" apps available, was a total scam. As a result, I stopped using dating apps altogether, and I will never look back.
